10011nam a22010215i 9781641892612DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a2020468526  a97816418926127 a10.1515/97816418926122doi  a(DE-B1597)542056  a(OCoLC)1129015651  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB-LDS00aJA84.E9bI34 2019. 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a18900aIdeology in the Middle Ages :bApproaches from Southwestern Europe /ced. by Flocel Sabaté. 1aLeeds : bArc Humanities Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (468 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCARMEN monographs and studies00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tForeword -- tIntroduction. Ideology in the Middle Ages -- tPART ONE: IDEOLOGY - A DEFINITION OF POWER -- tChapter 1. Ideology and Social Order -- tChapter 2. Auctoritas, potestas: Concepts of Power in Medieval Spain -- tChapter 3. Kingship in Isidore of Seville's Historical Work: A Political Interpretation of the Two Versions -- tChapter 4. The Quest for Ideology in Carolingian Times: Ecclesiological Patterns in the Latin West from the Eighth to the Early Tenth Centuries -- tChapter 5. Spiritual and Temporal Power in Raymond Llull's Arbor scientiae -- tPART TWO: IDEOLOGY - THE MANAGEMENT OF POWER -- tChapter 6. Regnum Gothorum and regnum Hispaniae in Medieval Spanish Christian Chronicles: Continuation, End, or Translation in their Accounts of the Arab Conquest -- tChapter 7. The Duel in Medieval Western Mentality -- tChapter 8. Royal Power and the Episcopacy: Eleventh- and Twelfth-Century Relics from Oviedo Cathedral -- tChapter 9. Chivalric Ideology in the Late Twelfth-Century Chanson d'Aspremont -- tChapter 10. Adoration of the Magi and Authority of the Medieval King: An Ambiguous Correlation -- tChapter 11. Ideology and Civic Ideal in French and German Cities in the Late Middle Ages -- tChapter 12. Economy and Religion in Late Medieval Italy: Markets in the Christian City -- tPART THREE: IDEOLOGY IN THE MIND -- tChapter 13. The Relationship between Mentality and Ideology: Acculturation and Christianization in Galicia, 500-1100 -- tChapter 14. The Foundation of the Franciscan Friary of the Sant Esperit, Valencia: Rule, Economy, and Royal Power in the Fifteenth-Century Crown of Aragon -- tChapter 15. Metamorphosis of the Green Man and the Wild Man in Portuguese Medieval Art -- tChapter 16. Military Models for Nobles in Zurara's Northern African Chronicles -- tChapter 17. Lorenzo the Magnificent: From Pseudo-Dynastic Polity to the Ottoman Model -- tChapter 18. Political Ideology and Legal Identity: The Reform of Juridical Deliberation in Aragon in the Fifteenth and Sixteenth Centuries -- tPART FOUR: THE MIDDLE AGES AS IDEOLOGY IN LATER ERAS -- tChapter 19. The Middle Ages: Support for a Counter-Revolutionary and Reactionary Ideology, 1830-1944 -- tChapter 20. The Middle Ages among Spanish Intellectuals of the First Half of the Twentieth Century0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPart of a trilogy involving research on identity and memory also, this substantial volume sets out to illuminate medieval thought through an in-depth and highly interdisciplinary study of ideology, interrogating the underlying values that inform the interpretive framework through which we might better understand men and women of the Middle Ages. An introductory chapter situates the Christian Church in the West as a framing ideology of the Middle Ages, analysing Christianity as a coherent narrative providing people with security through its integrated explanation of physical surroundings, social order, and spiritual hope. The book then goes on to consider ideology from four angles: as a means of defining power; as a way of managing power; ideology in the mind as an influence on daily living and how we understand societies; and finally, the ways in which ideology associated with the Middle Ages has exerted influence centuries later, conditioning understandings of past and present.  The individual chapters focus on concrete cases, giving preference to exemplars from southern Europe, a region with a large amount of documentation but which to date has occupied a relatively minor position in research into the Middle Ages. It is this emphasis that is acknowledged in the title of this book, Ideology in the Middle Ages: Approaches from Southwestern Europe, which is offered as a means of enriching and complicating study of the Middle Ages. This book has two companion volumes, dealing with the allied concepts of memory and identity as part of a larger project that seeks to map and interrogate the significance of all three concepts in the Middle Ages in the West.  aThis interdisciplinary volume sets out to illuminate medieval thought, and to consider how the underlying values of the Middle Ages exerted significant influence in medieval society in the West. The book situates the Christian Church in the West as a framing ideology of the Middle Ages, and considers ideology from four angles: as a means of defining power; as a way of managing power; ideology as an influence on daily living and societies; and the ways in which ideology associated with the Middle Ages continues to influence understandings of past and present. A focus on southern European case studies has been chosen as a means of enriching and complicating study of the Middle Ages.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aIdeologyzEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aideology, historical memory, political history, religion, medieval thought, Middle Ages.1 aAlonso Álvarez, Raquel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmalvi, Christian, econt